You are an expert in TypeScript, Node.js, Next.js 16 App Router, React, Shadcn UI and Tailwind.

Never invoke subagents!!!

Code Style and Structure

- Write concise, technical TypeScript code.
- Use functional and declarative programming patterns; avoid classes.
- Prefer iteration and modularization over code duplication.
- Use descriptive variable names with auxiliary verbs (e.g., isLoading, hasError).
- Structure files: exported component, subcomponents, helpers, static content, types.

Naming Conventions

- Use lowercase with dashes for directories (e.g., components/auth-wizard).
- Favor named exports for components.

TypeScript Usage

- Use TypeScript for all code; prefer interfaces over types.
- Avoid enums; use maps instead.
- Use functional components with TypeScript interfaces.

Syntax and Formatting

- Use the "function" keyword for pure functions.
- Avoid unnecessary curly braces in conditionals; use concise syntax for simple statements.
- Use declarative JSX.

UI and Styling

- Use Shadcn UI and Tailwind for components and styling.

Imports:

- Always import from absolute paths.

Database:

- Never manually create migration files, when new tables or updates are required; respond with sql query.
- Never manually update database types. This will be updated with bun run gen-types:local

Follow Next.js 16 docs for Data Fetching, Rendering, and Routing.

Translations/i18n:

- Each feature has its own messages folder: src/features/[feature-name]/messages/en.json and de.json
- NEVER update the global src/messages/ files for feature-specific translations
- Always check for existing feature-specific message files before adding translations
- Use the correct namespace structure that matches the existing translation keys in the feature

Code Comments:

- Write comments in English only
- Follow Clean Code principles for comments:
  - Comments should explain "why" not "what"
  - Avoid obvious comments that just restate the code
  - Use comments for complex business logic or non-obvious decisions
  - Keep comments up to date with code changes
  - Use JSDoc for public APIs and complex functions
  - Prefer self-documenting code over comments
